\meta{description}{Bridge layer connecting AlgebraicJulia/Catlab.jl to plurigrid/asi. Wires ACSets (attributed C-sets), wiring diagrams, decorated cospans, and the AlgebraicJulia ecosystem (AlgebraicDynamics, AlgebraicPetri, AlgebraicRewriting, Decapodes) into the ASI skill graph. ACSets generalize relational databases with categorical semantics; every diagram, network, and model in the ecosystem is an ACSet.}

\subtree{
\title{Catlab.jl x ASI Interleave}
\p{Bridge connecting AlgebraicJulia/Catlab.jl (categorical algebra in Julia) to the ASI skill graph (GF(3)-colored capability system).}

\subtree{
\title{Catlab Core Concepts (from DeepWiki deep-mine)}
\subtree{
\title{ACSets (Attributed C-Sets)}
\p{The universal data structure. A schema defines objects, homomorphisms (morphisms between objects), and attribute types. An ACSet instance is a functor from that schema category to Set.}

\pre{\startverb
# SchGraph: objects V, E; morphisms src: E->V, tgt: E->V
@present SchGraph(FreeSchema) begin
  V::Ob; E::Ob
  src::Hom(E,V); tgt::Hom(E,V)
end

# Attributed: add attribute types
@present SchWeightedGraph <: SchGraph begin
  T::AttrType
  weight::Attr(E,T)
end

const WeightedGraph = ACSetType(SchWeightedGraph, index=[:src,:tgt])
\stopverb}

\p{Every diagram, network, and model in the ecosystem is an ACSet.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Wiring Diagrams as ACSets}
\p{SchAttributedWiringDiagram with Box/InPort/OutPort/Wire. Boxes = operations/processes, wires = data flow. Used to compose dynamical systems, Petri nets, and more.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Decorated Cospans}
\p{Functor L: A -> X gives "open" ACSets. OpenGraph with hypergraph category structure. Operations: \code{\startverb compose\stopverb}, \code{\startverb otimes\stopverb} (monoidal product), \code{\startverb mcopy\stopverb}, \code{\startverb mmerge\stopverb}, \code{\startverb delete\stopverb}, \code{\startverb create\stopverb}. Enable compositional modeling of open systems.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Downstream Ecosystem}
\pre{\startverb
AlgebraicJulia/Catlab.jl (foundation)
  |- AlgebraicDynamics.jl     <- dynamical systems via decorated cospans
  |- AlgebraicPetri.jl        <- Petri nets with reaction network semantics
  |- AlgebraicRewriting.jl    <- DPO/SPO graph rewriting on ACSets
  |- CategoricalTensorNetworks.jl <- tensor contractions as string diagrams
  |- CombinatorialSpaces.jl   <- simplicial sets, discrete exterior calculus
  |- DataMigrations.jl        <- functorial data migration between schemas
  |- DiagrammaticEquations.jl <- physics equations as decorated cospans
  |- Decapodes.jl             <- multiphysics simulation via DEC
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{No probabilistic/inference capabilities} -- must come from downstream packages or bridges. This is where \code{\startverb monad-bayes-asi-interleave\stopverb} fills the gap.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{GF(3) Tripartite Tag}
\p{\code{\startverb algebraic-dynamics(-1) otimes catlab-asi-interleave(0) otimes algebraic-rewriting(+1) = 0\stopverb}}

\p{Dynamics (-1) x Foundation (0) x Rewriting (+1) = balanced categorical stack.}
}

\subtree{
\title{ASI Integration Points}
\subtree{
\title{1. acsets / acsets-algebraic-databases / acsets-relational-thinking to ACSets Core}
\p{Model the ASI skill graph as an ACSet for relational querying:}

\pre{\startverb
@present SchASISkills(FreeSchema) begin
  Skill::Ob; Edge::Ob; Hub::Ob
  src::Hom(Edge,Skill); tgt::Hom(Edge,Skill)
  hub_ref::Hom(Hub,Skill)
  SkillName::AttrType; TritVal::AttrType; Category::AttrType
  name::Attr(Skill,SkillName)
  trit::Attr(Skill,TritVal)        # -1, 0, +1
  category::Attr(Skill,Category)   # development | meta | ai-agents | ...
end

const ASISkills = ACSetType(SchASISkills, index=[:src,:tgt,:hub_ref])
skills = ASISkills()

# Conjunctive query: all GF(3)-balanced triads
gf3_triads(s) = filter(parts(s,:Edge)) do e
  t_src = s[s[e,:src], :trit]
  t_tgt = s[s[e,:tgt], :trit]
  (t_src + t_tgt) % 3 == 0
end
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. algebraic-rewriting / topos-adhesive-rewriting to DPO/SPO Rewriting}
\p{Double-pushout rewriting for safe skill graph mutation (MONOTONIC_SKILL_INVARIANT):}

\pre{\startverb
using AlgebraicRewriting

# DPO rule: add bridge skill to hub (never delete)
# L -> K <- R where |R| >= |L| always
add_bridge_rule = Rule(
  ACSetTransformation(L, K),   # L: match hub pattern
  ACSetTransformation(R, K),   # R: hub + new bridge skill
)
new_skills = rewrite(add_bridge_rule, current_skills)
@assert nparts(new_skills, :Skill) >= nparts(current_skills, :Skill)
\stopverb}

\p{SPO rewriting available for partial matches (non-adhesive contexts).}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. discopy / discopy-operads to Wiring Diagram Composition}
\p{Catlab's wiring diagrams and DisCoPy's string diagrams are the same mathematical object:}

\pre{\startverb
# ASI skill composition as wiring diagram
wd = @program SchSkillOp (validator::Val, coordinator::Coord, generator::Gen) begin
  validated = validator(input)
  coordinated = coordinator(validated)
  result = generator(coordinated)
  return result
end
# This WiringDiagram ACSet can be exported to DisCoPy format
\stopverb}

\p{Bridge: Julia WiringDiagram ACSet <-> Python DisCoPy Diagram via JSON serialization.}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. topos-catcolab / catcolab-* to CatColab Collaborative Modeling}
\p{CatColab is the web frontend to Catlab. Skills: \code{\startverb catcolab-ologs\stopverb}, \code{\startverb catcolab-petri-nets\stopverb}, \code{\startverb catcolab-stock-flow\stopverb}, \code{\startverb catcolab-causal-loop\stopverb}, \code{\startverb catcolab-decapodes\stopverb}. All CatColab models are ACSets underneath.}
}

\subtree{
\title{5. interaction-nets to Decorated Cospans / Hypergraph Categories}
\p{Decorated cospans give OpenGraph a hypergraph category structure. Operations: \code{\startverb compose\stopverb} (sequential), \code{\startverb otimes\stopverb} (parallel), \code{\startverb mcopy\stopverb} (fan-out), \code{\startverb mmerge\stopverb} (fan-in), \code{\startverb delete\stopverb}, \code{\startverb create\stopverb}. Interaction nets are the computational model; decorated cospans are the categorical semantics.}
}

\subtree{
\title{6. crn-topology to AlgebraicPetri Reaction Networks}
\pre{\startverb
using AlgebraicPetri

# Chemical reaction network as Petri net ACSet
sir_model = LabelledPetriNet([:S,:I,:R],
  :infection => ((:S,:I) => (:I,:I)),
  :recovery  => (:I => :R)
)
# Compose via decorated cospans
open_sir = Open(sir_model, [:S], [:R])
\stopverb}

\p{Connects to \code{\startverb crn-topology\stopverb} for topological analysis of reaction networks.}
}

\subtree{
\title{7. dynamical-system-functor / coupled-system to AlgebraicDynamics}
\pre{\startverb
using AlgebraicDynamics, Catlab

# Open continuous dynamical system
rb_system = ContinuousResourceSharer{Float64}(
  [:temperature, :velocity, :pressure],
  (u, p, t) -> rb_dynamics(u, p, t)
)
# Compose via wiring diagram
full_system = oapply(boundary_diagram, [rb_system, thermal_bc])
solution = solve(ODEProblem(full_system, u0, tspan), Tsit5())
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{8. julia-scientific to Julia Runtime for Catlab}
\p{Catlab requires Julia >= 1.10. Entry points: \code{\startverb julia-scientific\stopverb}, \code{\startverb julia-gay\stopverb}. Enzyme.jl autodiff works with AlgebraicDynamics ODE solvers.}
}

\subtree{
\title{9. topos-unified / topos-generate to Topos-Theoretic Foundations}
\p{Catlab implements presentable categories, limits/colimits, Kan extensions. The topos-theoretic skills (\code{\startverb topos-unified\stopverb}, \code{\startverb topos-generate\stopverb}, \code{\startverb effective-topos\stopverb}) provide the foundation that Catlab operationalizes in code.}
}

\subtree{
\title{10. monad-bayes-asi-interleave to Fills Probabilistic Gap}
\p{Catlab has \strong{no built-in probabilistic inference}. \code{\startverb monad-bayes-asi-interleave\stopverb} provides SMC/MCMC/PMMH/RMSMC stacks. The bridge: Catlab composes the model structure, monad-bayes performs inference on it.}
}

\subtree{
\title{11. vertex-ai-protein-interleave to Protein Reaction Networks}
\p{AlgebraicPetri reaction networks model biochemical pathways. Protein folding/docking pipelines from \code{\startverb vertex-ai-protein-interleave\stopverb} can use Catlab ACSets to represent reaction networks, pathway composition, and multi-target drug interaction graphs.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{ASI Skill Graph as an ACSet (Self-Modeling)}
\p{The ASI skill graph itself is naturally an ACSet:}

\pre{\startverb
# Skills = objects, edges = morphisms, GF(3) trits = attributes
@present SchASIGraph(FreeSchema) begin
  Skill::Ob
  Edge::Ob
  src::Hom(Edge,Skill)
  tgt::Hom(Edge,Skill)
  # Attribute types
  Name::AttrType; Trit::AttrType; Role::AttrType; Version::AttrType
  # Attributes
  name::Attr(Skill,Name)
  trit::Attr(Skill,Trit)          # GF(3): -1, 0, +1
  role::Attr(Skill,Role)          # BRIDGE | HUB | LEAF | ERGODIC
  version::Attr(Skill,Version)
  edge_type::Attr(Edge,Name)      # :citation | :behavioral | :trit_equiv
end

# Invariants as ACSet constraints:
# 1. MONOTONIC: nparts(g, :Skill) >= 1360 (never decreases)
# 2. GF3_CONSERVATION: for any triad (s1,s2,s3), sum of trits = 0 mod 3
# 3. HUB_REACHABILITY: 17 hub skills; every leaf reachable from >= 1 hub
\stopverb}

\p{This enables: conjunctive queries over the skill graph, functorial data migration between schema versions, DPO rewriting for safe skill addition, and wiring diagram visualization of skill pipelines.}
}

